ST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gwyn ap Gruffydd was born in 1150, in Wales, his father, Gruffydd ap Beli, was 16 and his mother, Lady Gruffydd, was 38. He had at least 1 daughter with Annes ferch Tudur. He died in 1201, in Wales, United Kingdom, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1150–1201":"1150–1201","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1135–1150":"1135–1150","1113–Female":"1113–Surnud","1149":"1149","1 August 1180":"1. august 1180","1201":"1201","1113":"1113","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1165":"1165","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","West Wales, Wales":"West Wales, Wales","Cegidfa, Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, United Kingdom","<Wales>":"Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1150–1201":"1150–1201","1135–Female":"1135–Kuollut","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1180–Female":"1180–Kuollut","1135–1150":"1135–1150","1113–Female":"1113–Kuollut","1149":"1149","1 August 1180":"1. elokuuta 1180","1201":"1201","1113":"1113","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1165":"1165","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Wales":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","West Wales, Wales":"West Wales, Wales","Cegidfa, Powys, Wales":"Powys, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","<Wales>":"Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1150–1201":"1150–1201","1135–Female":"1135–Décédée","1165–Female":"1165–Décédée","1180–Female":"1180–Décédée","1135–1150":"1135–1150","1113–Female":"1113–Décédée","1149":"1149","1 August 1180":"1 août 1180","1201":"1201","1113":"1113","1135":"1135","1200":"1200","1165":"1165","1150":"1150","1180":"1180","Wales":"Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","West Wales, Wales":"West Wales, Galles","Cegidfa, Powys, Wales":"Powys, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","<Wales>":"Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Gwyn ap Gruffydd est né en 1150, à Galles, son père, Gruffydd ap Beli, avait 16 ans et sa mère, Lady Gruffydd, avait 38 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Annes ferch Tudur. Il est décédé en 1201, à Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, à l’âge de 